%I A394840 #5 Apr 09 2026 21:40:25
%S A394840 9,11,13,15,17,16,17,19,21,20,21,23,22,23,25,24,25,27,26,27,29,28,29,
%T A394840 28,29
%N A394840 Minimum number of triangular cells in a connected polyiamond enclosing an interior hole of exactly n empty triangular cells.
%C A394840 A polyiamond is a connected figure of edge-joined equilateral triangles on the triangular lattice. Each cell has exactly 3 edge-neighbors. A "hole" is a maximal connected component of empty cells completely surrounded by occupied cells and not reachable from the exterior. Both the shell (occupied cells) and the hole must be connected.
%C A394840 The sequence is non-monotonic: a(6) < a(5), a(10) < a(9), a(13) < a(12), a(16) < a(15), a(19) < a(18), a(22) < a(21), a(24) < a(23). Drops occur when a more compact hole shape becomes available with smaller perimeter.
%C A394840 Triangular grid analog of A283056 (square grid), where a(n) = A027709(n) + 3. The additive constant "+3" appears in both formulas, suggesting a topological invariant across regular planar tilings.
%C A394840 Proof sketch. Let S be a minimum shell enclosing hole H with |H| = n cells and p = A067628(n) the minimum perimeter of H. (1) By minimality, the adjacency graph of S is a tree (any cycle would allow removing a cell while preserving enclosure), so S union H is simply connected. (2) By the discrete isoperimetric inequality on the triangular lattice, the outer perimeter of S union H satisfies L_out >= A067628(n + |S|). (3) The strict inequality 6n > (p-2)^2 (from the definition of A067628), combined with a parity argument (perimeter and cell count share parity), forces |S| >= 2p + 3 in the non-drop case and |S| >= 2p + 4 at drop positions.
%C A394840 Computed using a SAT solver (CaDiCaL via PySAT) with CEGAR for shell and hole connectivity. Top-down search proves optimality: SAT at k cells, UNSAT at k-1.
%H A394840 _Peter Exley_, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A394840">Solver code, data, and figures</a>, GitHub.
%F A394840 a(n) = 2*A067628(n) + 3 + [A067628(n) < A067628(n-1)] for n >= 1, where [P] is the Iverson bracket and A067628(0) = 0 by convention.
%e A394840 For n=1, the hole is a single triangle, so a(1)=9.
%e A394840 For n=2, the hole is a 2-iamond (rhombus), so a(2)=11.
%e A394840 For n=3, the hole is a 3-iamond (trapezoid), so a(3)=13.
%e A394840 For n=4, the hole is a 4-iamond (diamond), so a(4)=15.
%e A394840 For n=5, the hole is a 5-iamond (chevron), so a(5)=17.
%e A394840 For n=6, the hole is a compact 6-iamond (hexagon), so a(6)=16. This is the first drop: a(6) < a(5) because the hexagonal hole has smaller perimeter than the optimal 5-iamond.
%Y A394840 Cf. A067628 (minimum edge-perimeter of n-cell polyiamond), A283056 (square grid analog), A070764 (number of polyiamonds with holes), A327896 (minimum tiles for polyiamond with n separate holes), A027709 (minimum perimeter of n-cell polyomino).
%K A394840 nonn,more
